post_text:
We appreciate the support of our families and our community for the successful start of the 2020-2021 school year.

The summer program that provided free meals during the Covid closure has been extended through December 31, 2020. This entitles ALL our students grades PK-12 to receive FREE breakfasts and lunches from September 1, 2020 through the end of the semester on December 18, 2020. Families with students enrolled virtually can also receive free lunches. If your child attends virtually, contact the Board Office at 732-4426 for details and to sign your child up. Students attending in-person do not need to sign up. They are automatically free with each meal they eat while at school.

The deadline to confirm your choice between in-person attendance and virtual/distance learning is on Tuesday, September 15. At that point we ask you to commit to either continuing in-person or attending virtually.

post_text:
The CC Warhawks opened their season on the right foot😉

Kaitlyn King ran a 11:27:17, placing 10th
Abigail Poole ran a 12:21:19, placing 16th for the middle school girl's race. This was their first race!

Brett Payne, a newcomer, ran a 9:44:78, placing 7th!
Keaton Gibbs ran a 9:59:26, placing 9th, "single digits"
Dominic Rippeto ran a 10:32:49, placing 12th
Everett Pratt ran 11:15:17, placing 12th for the middle school boys race.

Brennan Bouse ran his first High school meet at 21:36:46, placing 17th in a varsity boys race!

Thank you for all those who came and supported our CC athletes!! We appreciate it!

post_text: We'd like to thank everyone for the patience as we find our groove with the new elementary pick-up and drop off procedures. With your help, we have greatly reduced the amount of time it's taken to get all of the students dropped off and picked up at the end of the day. We realize that traffic on the city streets is still an issue. To help reduce the number of cars waiting on the city streets we're making an adjustment to the path to the pickup lanes. We will now direct cars down each lane of the parking lot before entering either of the pickup lanes. This will get more cars off the streets and allow regular traffic to flow more freely. We are trying this first at pick-up, and if all goes well we will do the same during drop off. Thank you again for doing your part to make drop off and pick-up as efficient and safe as possible at Bourbon Elementary.

Warhawk Athletics Booster Club
August 22 at 1:13 PM ·

I am pleased to announce that we have booked comedian Jerad Langley for the 2021 Blue and White night. To be held on March 6. At Heartland Farms. Tickets will be going on sale soon.
Jerad Langley is a high energy comedian who's rural upbringing, and military service, combined with some world travel, have shaped his particular perspective on life. He travels all over the country performing in small towns with The Veterans of Comedy and Dirt Road Comedy. He has performed at comedy clubs, colleges, dive bars, pizza joints, bowling alleys and one awkward family reunion. Available for kids birthday parties (but not recommended)

Registration paper work has been mailed home earlier this week. You should be receiving the registration forms in the mail. Open enrollment at the middle school is set for August 11th for last names that begin with the letters A-M. and August 13th for the last names that begin with the letters N-Z. Open enrollment for both days will be from 11:00-6:00 at the middle school office.

Remember the link is to declare if your student will be attending in-person or virtually. Please complete this by August 12th at 1:00 P.M. If you have multiple students you will need to fill this out for each of your students. Families must choose one of these learning options and commit to following it for the duration of the first semester. However, there will be a 15 school day trial period for these modes of learning. Students will have until September 16 to commit fully to virtual/distance learning or in-person learning.

CCR-I families:
Immunization letters were mailed out last week. If you receive one, please follow up with your child's physician or Health Department. If your child has already received the required immunizations, please turn a copy in to the school office or fax to the school nurse at 573-732-4407; or email to negrettig@warhawks.k12.mo.us.
Also, if your child has asthma, food allergies, seizures, or diabetes, please provide the school nurse with an Emergency Action Plan from your child's physician & the appropriate medication/equipment (ex. spacer for asthma rescue inhaler).
Thank you for your cooperation!
CCR-I School Nurses

Yesterday, we shared information with our member schools on considerations. The MSHSAA Board of Directors and MSHSAA Sports Medicine Advisory Committee (SMAC) offer this document as guidance on how our state association can consider approaching the many components of “opening up” sports and activities in preparation for the fall seasons, and beyond.

The risk of coronavirus transmission will still be present to some degree as school activities begin in August and possibly through the 2020-2021 school year. Students and their families, along with school personnel must recognize these risks and implement best practices to reasonably mitigate these risks.

*Please send a water bottle daily.

*Students from the same household will be required to sit together on the bus.
*Students are allowed one pick-up and one drop-off location.

post_text: The Bourbon School Board welcomes Matt Peregoy as the new high school principal. Peregoy will be transitioning to BHS after a decade at Sullivan High School, instructing Industrial Arts and coaching the wrestling team. Dr Gibbs stated, “Matt brings a strong background across different disciplines. He has been a core teacher, was involved in Project Lead the Way, and has a proven record in motivating people.” Mr. Perogy´s advocacy for Project Lead the Way, a national effort that encourages student interest in studying engineering and science-related fields, is conducive to the school district's vision to advance its STEM program. Dr. Gibbs feels that Peregoy´s background in PLTW could be instrumental in finding the right person for that position. Mr. Peregoy is proactively setting goals and taking action, meeting with the administration team and the high school staff, when possible. Mr. Peregoy will officially begin serving as the Bourbon High School principal on July 1, 2020.

post_text:
Warhawk Nation would like to welcome Kelli Bailey as the new head volleyball coach at Bourbon High School. Mrs. Bailey graduated from BHS in 2009, playing volleyball all four years. Continuing her volleyball career, she played at the college level. Mrs. Bailey played two years at ECC, followed by two years at Lindenwood University Belleville. After graduating from college, Mrs. Bailey taught six years at Clark Vitt Elementary for Union R-XI School District. She began her coaching career at Union, coaching JV for one year and 8th grade for two years. The past five years, she was the head varsity coach for Union. Mrs. Bailey will be teaching third grade at Bourbon Elementary, while coaching JH Volleyball and Varsity Volleyball at BHS, next fall. Welcome home Mrs. Bailey!
#WarhawkStrong

Bourbon Elementary and Middle School Library
March 31 at 6:57 PM ·

Here is another option for us all for eBooks: https://www.myon.com/school/readathome
This is the Myon website by Renaissance, and it has lots of great testing books. The username for this site is readnow and the password is myon no matter what grade or classroom you are in. Please note that the A.R. level is not easy to find. Once you have chosen a book and clicked on it, you have to click on the blue rectangle with the lowercase "i" in it. Then, look in the right hand column. The first thing in that column is "ATOS" which means the same as A.R. level. So...the book I am showing you in the pictures is a level 3.0. Just remember, you have to look for "ATOS". That is a little different than we are used to, but we can do it! I know we can!
Here's the username and password again:
Username: readnow
Password: myon

Bourbon's Student Artists
March 19 at 1:24 PM ·

Middle School Drawing Activity: FORMS

This worksheet from Menlo Park Art, shows how to add value (light and darkness) to basic 3-D forms using a variety of shading techniques. Practice shading a cylinder, cube, cone, and sphere using hatching, crosshatching, stippling, and blending. Try to make your drawings look like the worksheet. Then, set up a still life using items from your home that have simple forms as well. Canned goods, sports equipment, tools, toys, and boxed food items are a good place to start. Choose your favorite shading technique to add value to your drawing.

post_text:
14 Days of Conditioning

The MSHSAA Office will not waive the requirement to have 14 days of conditioning under the supervision of the coach. Therefore, giving a student a workout plan will not count toward the requirement while schools are not in session and unable to practice at the school. When the students return this spring, they will start with the number of practices they had completed up to this date. However, if the school wishes to be more restrictive to require more than 14 practices, the school can.
